  "prompt": "Why can't someone have a cake and eat it too?",
  "response": "The phrase \"You can't have your cake and eat it too\" is an idiom that means you can't have something both ways or enjoy two incompatible alternatives simultaneously. \n\nThe literal meaning suggests that once you eat a cake, you no longer have it. In other words, you can't preserve something and consume it at the same time. \n\nIn practical terms, it means you can't have the benefits of two opposing choices. For example, someone can't want to keep a job but also skip work whenever they feel like it, or want the advantages of a relationship without the commitment.\n\nThe saying essentially highlights the need to make choices and accept that sometimes you can't have everything exactly the way you want it.",
